---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const sections = [
  ["overview", "Overview"],
  ["information", "Information we handle"],
  ["uses", "How we use information"],
  ["sharing", "How we share information"],
  ["retention", "Retention and deletion"],
  ["security", "Security"],
  ["choices", "Your choices and rights"],
  ["international", "International processing"],
  ["children", "Children"],
  ["changes", "Changes"],
  ["contact", "Contact"],
] as const;
---

<Layout
  title="Privacy Policy — T3 Code"
  description="How T3 Tools, Inc. handles information when you use T3 Code and t3.codes."
>
  <div class="policy-page">
    <header class="policy-hero">
      <p class="eyebrow">Legal / T3 Code</p>
      <h1>Privacy Policy</h1>
      <p class="policy-lede">
        T3 Code is designed to work locally first. This policy explains what stays on your devices,
        what is sent to services you choose, and what T3 Tools handles when you use our website or
        optional cloud features.
      </p>
      <dl class="policy-dates" aria-label="Policy dates">
        <div>
          <dt>Effective</dt>
          <dd>July 14, 2026</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Last updated</dt>
          <dd>July 14, 2026</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </header>

    <div class="policy-rule" aria-hidden="true"></div>

    <div class="policy-layout">
      <aside class="policy-nav" aria-label="On this page">
        <p class="policy-nav-label">On this page</p>
        <ol>
          {sections.map(([id, label], index) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`#${id}`}>
                <span>{String(index + 1).padStart(2, "0")}</span>
                {label}
              </a>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ol>
      </aside>

      <article class="policy-copy">
        <section id="overview">
          <p class="section-number">01</p>
          <h2>Overview</h2>
          <p>
            This Privacy Policy describes how T3 Tools, Inc. (“T3 Tools,” “we,” “us,” or “our”)
            accesses, collects, uses, and shares information when you visit <strong>t3.codes</strong>,
            use the T3 Code desktop or mobile applications, or use optional T3 Connect features
            (together, the “Services”).
          </p>
          <div class="architecture-note">
            <p class="architecture-label">Local-first architecture</p>
            <p>
              You can use T3 Code without creating a T3 account. In direct-connection mode, coding
              sessions run in an environment you control. Session content travels between your T3
              Code clients, that environment, and the coding-agent providers you configure; the
              content does not need to pass through T3 Connect.
            </p>
          </div>
          <p>
            If you choose to sign in and enable T3 Connect, we process the account, environment,
            device, notification, and operational information needed to connect your devices and
            provide those features. Depending on your connection method, encrypted session traffic
            may also pass through infrastructure used to connect your devices.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="information">
          <p class="section-number">02</p>
          <h2>Information we handle</h2>

          <h3>Account information</h3>
          <p>
            If you sign in, we receive account identifiers and profile information from our
            authentication provider and the identity provider you select. This may include your
            name, email address, profile image, user ID, authentication tokens, and sign-in method.
          </p>

          <h3>Environment, connection, and device information</h3>
          <p>
            We process information required to connect and secure your environments, such as
            environment and device identifiers, labels you assign, public keys, connection
            endpoints, credential hashes, connection status, app version, operating-system version,
            and notification preferences. If you enable notifications or Live Activities, we also
            process push tokens and activity information such as project and thread titles, model
            name, status, and activity headline.
          </p>

          <h3>Coding content and files</h3>
          <p>
            T3 Code lets you send prompts, agent responses, command and terminal output, file names
            and paths, source files, diffs, review comments, images, and other attachments. This
            content is sent to the environment and coding-agent provider you choose so they can
            perform your request. When you use T3 Connect, limited activity details may be processed
            to provide connection status and notifications. We do not use your source code, prompts,
            or agent responses to train AI models.
          </p>

          <h3>Operational and website data</h3>
          <p>
            We and our service providers may automatically receive request timestamps, IP address,
            browser or app type and version, device and operating-system information, pages visited,
            connection events, latency, error details, and diagnostic traces. T3 Code diagnostics
            are used to operate, secure, and troubleshoot the Services—not for advertising.
            Authentication headers are redacted from our relay request traces.
          </p>

          <h3>Device permissions</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Camera:</strong> used when you choose to scan a pairing QR code. Camera frames
              are processed on your device.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Photos and files:</strong> items you select are accessed only to preview them or
              attach them to a request you initiate.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Notifications:</strong> used only if you enable agent-status notifications or
              Live Activities.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Local network:</strong> used to discover or connect to T3 Code environments on
              your local network or private tailnet.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Local app storage</h3>
          <p>
            T3 Code stores connection settings, credentials, preferences, drafts, and cached thread,
            file, branch, and server metadata on your device. Credentials and session tokens use
            platform-provided protected storage where supported. Locally stored information is not
            collected by T3 Tools unless it is transmitted as part of a feature you use.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="uses">
          <p class="section-number">03</p>
          <h2>How we use information</h2>
          <p>We use information to:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>provide, maintain, synchronize, and troubleshoot the Services;</li>
            <li>authenticate users and protect accounts, devices, and environments;</li>
            <li>link devices and environments and deliver optional notifications;</li>
            <li>respond to support requests and communicate service-related information;</li>
            <li>monitor reliability, prevent abuse, and investigate security incidents;</li>
            <li>comply with law and enforce our agreements; and</li>
            <li>improve T3 Code using aggregated or de-identified operational information.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            We do not sell personal information, use it for targeted advertising, or use T3 Code
            content to train AI models.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="sharing">
          <p class="section-number">04</p>
          <h2>How we share information</h2>
          <p>We share information only as needed with the following categories of recipients:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Providers you choose.</strong> Prompts, files, and related content are sent to
              coding agents and AI providers configured in your environment, such as OpenAI,
              Anthropic, or other providers you select. Their terms and privacy policies apply.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Service providers.</strong> We use vendors for authentication (Clerk and the
              identity provider you choose), cloud hosting and networking, website hosting and CDN
              delivery, app updates (Expo), operational diagnostics (Axiom), and email or support.
              These providers process information for us under their own contractual and privacy
              obligations.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Platform providers.</strong> Apple or Google may process device, store,
              authentication, update, and push-notification information under their policies.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Legal and safety recipients.</strong> We may disclose information when
              reasonably necessary to comply with law, protect rights and safety, investigate abuse,
              or establish or defend legal claims.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Business transfers.</strong> Information may be transferred as part of a
              merger, financing, acquisition, reorganization, bankruptcy, or sale of assets, subject
              to applicable law.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>We may also share information at your direction or with your consent.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="retention">
          <p class="section-number">05</p>
          <h2>Retention and deletion</h2>
          <p>
            Information stored only on your device remains there until you clear it, remove the
            relevant connection, or uninstall the app. The mobile app provides cache controls under
            <strong>Settings → App → Client Storage</strong>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We retain account, environment-link, device-registration, notification, and security
            information while your account or the relevant feature is active and for as long as
            reasonably necessary to provide the Services, protect them from abuse, comply with law,
            and resolve disputes. Operational diagnostic traces are configured to expire after 30
            days. Some records may remain longer in backups or where retention is required for
            security, fraud prevention, or legal compliance.
          </p>
          <p>
            To request deletion of your T3 account and associated T3 Connect data, email
            <a href="mailto:privacy@t3.chat">privacy@t3.chat</a> from the email address associated
            with your account. We may need to verify your identity. Deleting a T3 account does not
            delete information held by an environment or coding-agent provider you control; contact
            those providers or delete that information directly.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="security">
          <p class="section-number">06</p>
          <h2>Security</h2>
          <p>
            We use administrative, technical, and organizational safeguards designed to protect
            personal information. These include encrypted network transport, scoped and proof-bound
            access tokens for supported connection flows, protected credential storage, and
            redaction of authorization headers from relay diagnostics. No method of transmission or
            storage is completely secure, so we cannot guarantee absolute security.
          </p>
          <p>
            You are responsible for securing the environments, agent-provider accounts, credentials,
            and networks that you connect to T3 Code.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="choices">
          <p class="section-number">07</p>
          <h2>Your choices and rights</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Use local or direct connections without signing in to a T3 account.</li>
            <li>Disconnect environments, sign out, and clear local caches from Settings.</li>
            <li>Grant or revoke camera, photo, local-network, and notification permissions in your device settings.</li>
            <li>Disable optional notifications and Live Activities in the app.</li>
            <li>Request access, correction, or deletion by contacting us.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Depending on where you live, you may have additional rights to access, correct, delete,
            restrict, or object to processing of your personal information, or to receive a portable
            copy. You may also have the right to appeal our response or complain to a data-protection
            authority. We will honor applicable rights after verifying your request.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="international">
          <p class="section-number">08</p>
          <h2>International processing</h2>
          <p>
            T3 Tools is based in the United States, and we and our service providers may process
            information in the United States and other countries. Where required, we use lawful
            safeguards for international transfers of personal information.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="children">
          <p class="section-number">09</p>
          <h2>Children</h2>
          <p>
            The Services are not directed to children under 13, and we do not knowingly collect
            personal information from children under 13. If you believe a child has provided us with
            personal information, contact us so we can take appropriate action.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="changes">
          <p class="section-number">10</p>
          <h2>Changes to this policy</h2>
          <p>
            We may update this Privacy Policy as T3 Code and our practices change. We will post the
            revised policy at this URL and update the date above. If a change is material, we may
            provide additional notice through the Services or another appropriate channel.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="contact">
          <p class="section-number">11</p>
          <h2>Contact</h2>
          <p>Questions, privacy requests, and deletion requests can be sent to:</p>
          <address>
            <strong>T3 Tools, Inc.</strong><br />
            2261 Market Street #5309<br />
            San Francisco, CA 94114<br />
            United States
          </address>
          <a class="contact-link" href="mailto:privacy@t3.chat">privacy@t3.chat</a>
        </section>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .policy-page {
    width: min(1120px, calc(100% - 64px));
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: clamp(72px, 10vw, 132px) 0 112px;
  }

  .policy-hero {
    max-width: 820px;
    animation: fade-in 0.8s ease-out both;
  }

  .policy-hero h1 {
    margin-top: 18px;
    font-size: clamp(3.4rem, 8vw, 7.4rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.065em;
    line-height: 0.9;
  }

  .policy-lede {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin-top: 34px;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: clamp(1.05rem, 1.8vw, 1.3rem);
    line-height: 1.65;
    letter-spacing: -0.012em;
  }

  .policy-dates {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 36px;
    margin-top: 38px;
  }

  .policy-dates div {
    display: grid;
    gap: 4px;
  }

  .policy-dates dt,
  .policy-nav-label,
  .section-number,
  .architecture-label {
    color: var(--fg-dim);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .policy-dates dd {
    color: var(--fg);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
  }

  .policy-rule {
    height: 1px;
    margin: 72px 0;
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--border-strong), var(--border) 65%, transparent);
  }

  .policy-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 210px minmax(0, 720px);
    gap: clamp(64px, 10vw, 140px);
    align-items: start;
  }

  .policy-nav {
    position: sticky;
    top: 88px;
  }

  .policy-nav ol {
    display: grid;
    gap: 2px;
    margin-top: 16px;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .policy-nav a {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 24px 1fr;
    gap: 9px;
    padding: 7px 0;
    color: var(--fg-dim);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    transition: color 0.16s ease;
  }

  .policy-nav a span {
    color: var(--fg-faint);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.64rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .policy-nav a:hover {
    color: var(--fg);
  }

  .policy-copy {
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .policy-copy section {
    scroll-margin-top: 104px;
  }

  .policy-copy section + section {
    margin-top: 82px;
    padding-top: 82px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .section-number {
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .policy-copy h2 {
    margin: 8px 0 28px;
    color: var(--fg);
    font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3vw, 2.45rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
    line-height: 1.1;
  }

  .policy-copy h3 {
    margin: 32px 0 10px;
    color: var(--fg);
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: -0.015em;
  }

  .policy-copy p,
  .policy-copy li,
  .policy-copy address {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    font-style: normal;
    line-height: 1.78;
  }

  .policy-copy p + p {
    margin-top: 18px;
  }

  .policy-copy strong {
    color: var(--fg);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .policy-copy ul {
    display: grid;
    gap: 12px;
    margin: 18px 0 20px;
    padding-left: 1.2rem;
  }

  .policy-copy li {
    padding-left: 7px;
  }

  .policy-copy li::marker {
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .policy-copy a {
    color: var(--fg);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-decoration-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 55%, transparent);
    text-underline-offset: 4px;
    transition: text-decoration-color 0.16s ease;
  }

  .policy-copy a:hover {
    text-decoration-color: var(--accent);
  }

  .architecture-note {
    position: relative;
    margin: 30px 0;
    padding: 26px 28px 27px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border-strong);
    border-radius: 14px;
    background:
      linear-gradient(135deg, var(--accent-dim), transparent 55%),
      rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.015);
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .architecture-note::before {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0 auto 0 0;
    width: 2px;
    background: var(--accent);
  }

  .architecture-note .architecture-label {
    margin: 0 0 10px;
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .architecture-note p:last-child {
    color: var(--fg);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  address {
    margin-top: 20px;
  }

  .contact-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: 18px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 820px) {
    .policy-page {
      width: min(100% - 40px, 720px);
      padding-top: 56px;
      padding-bottom: 80px;
    }

    .policy-hero h1 {
      font-size: clamp(3.1rem, 16vw, 5rem);
    }

    .policy-rule {
      margin: 52px 0;
    }

    .policy-layout {
      display: block;
    }

    .policy-nav {
      display: none;
    }

    .policy-copy section + section {
      margin-top: 62px;
      padding-top: 62px;
    }
  }

  @media (max-width: 420px) {
    .policy-page {
      width: calc(100% - 32px);
      padding-top: 42px;
    }

    .policy-lede {
      margin-top: 26px;
      font-size: 1rem;
    }

    .policy-dates {
      gap: 24px;
    }

    .architecture-note {
      padding: 22px 20px;
    }

    .policy-copy p,
    .policy-copy li,
    .policy-copy address {
      font-size: 0.94rem;
    }
  }
</style>
